title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Model 67 Stainless Combat Masterpiece
postcontent:
This is one of the finest .38 Special revolvers ever made . . . the Model 67 Combat Masterpiece . . . and this is the finest example of that line: an early 1970s version with the stainless steel adjustable sights (later versions were blued steel sights, then plastic).  The K-frame revolvers are perfect for individuals with small hands, and a wide variety of aftermarket grips are available.

This is a 6-shot K-38 revolver with a 4" barrel and is more accurate than you are.  I fired 18 rounds at the range today, putting them all in a quarter sized grouping at 30 feet.  Double-action is smooth and easy, but single action breaks like glass at under 3oz which is better than a target grade 1911.  This is an excellent shooter, light to carry, and built to last a lifetime.  No internal lock or MIM parts on this classic 70s vintage Masterpiece . . . Smith & Wesson hasn't made revolvers of this quality in a very long time.

I am the second owner.  First owner claimed under 100 rounds through it since purchased new, and has been in storage ever since.  It is in 97% condition, which means "Like New" with minor handling marks.  This revolver is all stainless steel, inside and out, and has the original checkered walnut grips.

I recently purchased this gun, thinking it would be perfect for me, but I picked up a Ruger Custom Shop Speed Six that same week and decided I like that a little better.  This would be a PERFECT first gun as it is incredibly easy to load, unload, and fire accurately.  This is a much better choice for the novice than a magnum or an automatic pistol.  Being a stainless steel Smith, it will easily handle +P ammunition, although it is recommended to use standard pressure ammo for practice.

I have $600 into this and would like to get that same amount back in cash, and price is pretty firm as I don't need to sell and wouldn't mind keeping it. 

Trades I would be interested in include Smith & Wesson Airweights (442 specifically, but would consider 642, 438, 638) or a steel framed Centennial.  I might also consider a Officer or Commander sized 1911 with ambi safety, a Smith or Glock 10mm, NAA PUG or Short + cash, LCR38 + cash, CA Lite + cash.  Possibly a SIG P239 + cash on my end.  That is pretty much all I'm interested in.

"T" Aiming Point Calibrated To Eliminate Guesswork In Close-Range Targeting

The Brownells CQB T-Dot Sight is designed for combat and competition shooters who frequently address targets at close quarters. It corrects a common problem with combat-zeroed optics mounted on an AR-type rifle: the point of impact is significantly lower than the point of aim at close quarters distances. Built by EOTech exclusively for Brownells and based on the popular EOTech EXPS2, the CQB T-Dot eliminates the “guesstimating” when aiming at these targets. The reticle has 20 brightness settings selected using the control buttons on the left side and is powered by one CR-123 lithium battery (included), easily accessed through the side cap. Sealed, non-magnifying optics are fogproof, shatter-resistant, and anti-glare coated.
